				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">Mirroring is effectively a result of the address being bitmasked (due to not all of the address lines being used).  Therefore you can use bitmasking to easily accomplish mirroring:
<br />
<br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">u8 RAM&#91;0x800&#93;;&nbsp; // 0x800 bytes of system ram<br /><br />//...<br /><br />u8 Read_From_Address_Range_0000_1FFF&#40;u16 address&#41;<br />&#123;<br />&nbsp; return RAM&#91; address &amp; 0x07FF &#93;;&nbsp; // mask low bits to perform mirroring<br />&#125;<br /></div><br /><br />I'm also a fan of using function pointers to call a different function depending on the range the address falls in.  I forget the exact C syntax for it, but you probably get the idea:<br /><br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">typedef u8 &#40;*readfunction&#41;&#40;u16 address&#41;;<br /><br />readfunction readproc&#91;0x10&#93;;&nbsp; // 0x10 read functions, one for each 0x1000 block<br /><br />// on startup<br /><br />readproc&#91;0&#93; = read_ram;<br />readproc&#91;1&#93; = read_ram;<br />readproc&#91;2&#93; = read_ppu;<br />// etc<br /><br />// on read<br /><br />valueread = readproc&#91;address &gt;&gt; 12&#93;&#40;address&#41;;<br /></div></div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

